WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.840
Okay. Next is Dr. Alleman, who's going to tell us about a personalized approach to treating

00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:18.040
iatrogenic T-cell lymphoma from BCMA CAR-T. All right. Last talk. Thank you. Thank you again for

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:22.060
the invite. Today, I'm going to talk about CAR-T cell lymphoma that happened after silt-to-cell

00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:26.600
therapy. As we all know and have heard throughout this whole conference, silt-to-cell is great.

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:31.400
It keeps patients, we might even be getting to a cure. However, there is one thing that has been

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:35.600
occurring, and that's the secondary adverse events. These are just five cases published

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:39.860
last year of secondary T-cell lymphoma cases that have happened after silt-to-cell, and they all

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:44.640
have commonalities. Most of them have a chip mutation, and most of them present with skin

00:00:44.640 --> 00:00:49.700
tropism. And we at Mount Sinai also had a case. We had a case of a patient who came in, received

00:00:49.700 --> 00:00:56.500
silt-to-cell, went into remission, and then around day 190, came in with facial lesions and

00:00:56.500 --> 00:00:56.580
hypothermia. And we had a case of a patient who came in, received silt-to-cell, went into remission,

00:00:56.580 --> 00:01:01.940
and had hypercutaneous imaging on PET scan. So we wanted to know what was it at the time and how do

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:06.060
we treat it? So the first thing we did was work it up. We found that histology was showing that it

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:11.200
was CD3 positive and lacked CD4 and CD8s. And more importantly, it actually, through flow cytometry,

00:01:11.340 --> 00:01:16.040
had the CAR vector still in there. So it was a CAR-T T-cell lymphoma that showed the same thing

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:21.700
as the pathology. This was also present not only in the skin, but also was in the peripheral blood,

00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:26.400
lymph nodes, and bone marrow. When we looked at the genetic profile, we ended up seeing that

00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:32.900
this actually has an expansion of a previous ChIP-Tet2 clone, and there was a novel EZH2

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:37.820
clone that was present in this T-cell lymphoma. Additionally, the CAR itself had integrated into

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:43.000
the TIA1 gene. So we wanted to implement a personalized approach. The first thing we did

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:48.160
is we characteristically immunophenotyped it comprehensively. The first thing we found was

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:53.800
that it had CCR4. So we incorporated into the patient's regimen mogolizumab, and then we

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:56.540
actually did a high-throughput drug screening. So on the peripheral blood, we had a high-throughput

00:01:56.540 --> 00:02:01.040
blood. We extracted some of those malignant CAR-T cells and then tested them with 179 different

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:06.440
compounds and found the compound that would be most toxic to the CAR-T cells, but left endogenous

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:11.400
T-cells relatively without cytotoxicity. We found that the best class of drug for this was

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:16.980
anthracycline therapies. So we combined this anthracycline therapy using liposomal doxorubicin

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:22.280
and gensitabine with mogolizumab, and the patient had a fantastic response. So in the blue,

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:26.380
you see the endogenous T-cells going down as the tumor malignant CAR-T cells start expanding in the

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:30.100
peripheral blood. But as soon as we start initiating the personalized therapy, the CAR-T

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:34.980
cells were gone from the blood. They were gone from the bone marrow and the lesions cleared up

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:38.320
in the face, and the endogenous T-cells bounced right back. And on the right, you see the imaging

00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:42.940
showing the same thing where the patient entered a very good response. Not only that, he's been

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:48.340
in remission in myeloma and T-cell lymphoma for almost two years now. So this was a very

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:56.500
successful case, but we kept thinking, what drove it? What caused this pathogenesis of the T-cell

00:02:56.500 --> 00:03:01.000
and the TET2 and EZH2 both play suppressive roles, and that chip mutations, like I said,

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:05.820
was common in other cases that we have seen. And TA1 is a suppressive gene as well that has

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:09.300
transcriptional modifications, inflammatory responses in T-cells. We wanted to know which

00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:14.700
one was the driver of these three mutations that caused this T-cell lymphoma. So we aimed to test

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:19.180
it in the lab. We have a sample banked from the patient at the same time that we collected for

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:24.720
apheresis to send for Cilta-Cell, and we made lab-made CAR-Ts. And then this was done by our

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:25.440
postdoc, Ruja.

00:03:26.480 --> 00:03:31.380
We started knocking out the main genes of interest here. So we knocked out TET2, EZH2, and TA1.

00:03:32.220 --> 00:03:38.320
What we ended up seeing is that the proliferation was affected by these knockouts. So we started

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:42.380
doing combinations as well. The highest proliferative status that we saw from the

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:46.940
knockouts when we knocked out TET2 and EZH2, and that's in the yellow line in the graph.

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:51.260
But what we can tell is that the TET2 mutant actually itself also had a very high proliferative

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:56.460
advantage. So apart from proliferation advantage, we actually ended up seeing that

00:03:56.460 --> 00:04:02.560
the phenotype of these knockout cells actually shifted as we introduced them. So the control

00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:06.800
CAR-Ts in the first row, and then on the bottom, you see the TET2, EZH2 mutant. And you see that

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:10.480
it starts shifting to look like the malignant CAR-T cells that was in our patient. We see an

00:04:10.480 --> 00:04:18.160
increase of CCR4, which we attribute to skin tropism as CCR4 is a skin-homing chemokine.

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:23.200
We see the PD1 increase, and we see a loss of CD7 that's actually present in the double mutant,

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:26.280
and I'm not showing it in the single mutants, but the single mutant, the TET2 knockout,

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:29.940
actually had the same phenotypic change. From there, we wanted to see, did it affect the

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:34.880
function? We know that the CAR-Ts in our patient actually were inert. So we ended up doing a

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:39.780
functional assay in which we combined these CAR-T cells with myeloma cells and then assessed the

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:44.100
cytotoxicity. The red bar is a control CAR-Ts that we made at the same time as a phoresis.

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:48.760
The tumor CAR-Ts are CAR-Ts isolated straight, the malignant CAR-Ts isolated straight from the

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:53.360
patient's peripheral blood. And then the other graphs on the other columns on the right are the

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:56.340
different knockdown cytotoxicity. And what you can appreciate,

00:04:56.420 --> 00:05:03.900
is that the TET2 has the highest single knockdown reduction of cytotoxicity, while you get an even

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:08.860
greater augmented effect when you do the double knockout of TET2 and EZH2, indicating to us that

00:05:08.860 --> 00:05:13.580
TET2 may have been the main driver, but EZH2 definitely did attribute to increased

00:05:13.580 --> 00:05:16.380
inertness that we saw in the tumor CAR-Ts that were present.

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:21.580
And this is just a graph describing what the genomic characteristics of all the knockdowns

00:05:21.580 --> 00:05:26.400
that we ended up seeing. The TET2, like I said before, it had a very big increase in CAR-T growth

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:30.960
on the DISH. It also increased the differentiation markers that we saw in our patients on the DISH,

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:36.400
in our patients' actual malignant CAR-T cells and had the significant loss of cytotoxicity.

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:41.520
We don't see much changes with the TIA1 knockdown, so maybe the actual integration itself didn't

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:46.480
provide a significant shift, but we think that the combination between the TET2 and EZH2 are the main

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:52.080
drivers that are causing this malignancy that we saw in our patients. So in conclusion, we report

00:05:52.080 --> 00:05:56.380
a case where we had a patient with this adverse event that is rare, but it is something that we have to

00:05:56.380 --> 00:06:01.100
deal with. And we implemented a personalized approach by not only using comprehensive

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:06.800
immunophenotyping, but also high-throughput drug screening. And our in vitro modeling does

00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:13.400
indicate that the CHIP mutant that was expanded and the novel EZH2 loss contributed to the

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:16.860
malignant transformation by the increased proliferation, the change in the phenotypic

00:06:16.860 --> 00:06:20.480
behavior that look more in line to what we saw in our patient's tumor, and in general,

00:06:20.560 --> 00:06:24.080
reduction in functionality that we see that was present in our patient's tumor.

00:06:24.080 --> 00:06:26.360
And this is just important because monitoring

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:31.180
CHIP mutations in CAR-T could allow for early detection and mitigation of these side effects.

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:36.180
And we had a piper, not talking about TET2, but in TP53 mutations in which we saw that

00:06:36.180 --> 00:06:43.980
patients that had that were more likely to have MDS or AML as secondary malignancies. Thank you.
